00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:11.000
Okay, I see, Manuel, you had asked a question when you registered about Positron, and I'm seeing some excitement about Positron in the chat, too.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:27.000
And feel free to jump in if you want to add any more context to it. The question was, in what ways does Posit see using the best of both for R and Python development occurring in Positron?

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:30.000
Am I the only Manuel?

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:32.000
Yes, that's you.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:38.000
Yeah, and I guess, you know, I was going to add a different question slightly on this theme.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:42.000
So, I'll embellish it if you all allow me.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:48.000
I'm with Exxon Mobil, so I'm with a large enterprise, and we have many products, many solutions. One of them is Databricks.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:17:02.000
And I get the sense that the individuals very passionate in either community are accustomed to their IDE of choice, right? So it was RStudio or Spyder or whatever, and now maybe Positron.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:13.000
But I'm finding myself having to build solutions that are so large that I'm not certain if that's the right home anymore.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:28.000
So maybe the question can be, you know, what's the continuing value proposition for something like Positron when the landscape continues to change and the scale of things that people are being asked to build could grow, right?

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:43.000
So I get it if I'm modeling, if I'm deploying something to predict that IDE experience is very powerful, but for a lot of what I have to do for business intelligence or analytics, they just want to report.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:53.000
So I don't necessarily need that, right? So I kind of wandered. I hope I didn't get us too crazy.

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:56.000
I don't know if you want to take a stab at that, Wiz, or I can.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:18:20.000
Sure, sure. Well, so I don't know how much folks in this call know about Positron, but the idea of Positron was to develop the kind of – you can think of RStudio pioneered what we can think of as the classic four-pane data science layout with the console,

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:37.000
the code editor, the variables pane, and the plots pane. And so you can move between. And there's some other components like the connections pane for interacting with databases, the data viewer for being able to look at your data frames and your tabular data.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:52.000
But having each of those concepts as first-class citizens within a development environment is really powerful, and I think RStudio has shown that over the last 15 years with its enduring popularity.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:19:06.000
And so the idea with Positron is that we wanted to create that same kind of experience and make it available to Python users, but in a polyglot-first IDE.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:18.000
But it's kind of a difficult problem to build from the ground up something that works equally well in R and Python and supports all of those different components.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:33.000
So we chose to build Positron on top of the open-source VS Code codebase. So we have basically an extensive set of customizations and components that we've built on top of open-source VS Code.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:51.000
And we've created that kind of hybrid IDE where you can, within the IDE, you can have both an R session and a Python session running. And so you might have one tab that's an R program where you're doing something in R and then another tab that's Python.

00:19:51.000 --> 00:20:06.000
And whenever you switch contexts, it will change the session, the active session, and that will change the variables that are displayed, the plots, and the different components in that four-pane data science layout.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:22.000
You can imagine this has been an awful lot of engineering, but I think it reflects kind of how we as a business are thinking about building tools going forward, building things polyglot from the ground up.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:51.000
Similar ideas with Quarto and Connect is also kind of being built as a polyglot application and document publishing platform. So it's going to take a long time before Positron—well, I should qualify, it will take some time before Positron is able to reach the level of polish that RStudio has after 15 years.

00:20:51.000 --> 00:21:10.000
But it's an early-stage project. We're really interested in feedback and users. I think it will be available as a preview, kind of in preview alpha, beta form in Posit Workbench in the near future.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:37.000
I'm not sure, maybe in the first quarter of next year. And then we're hoping for it to become generally GA production toward the end of next year or early 2026 in terms of timeline. But we're making a big investment there and getting those, supporting those, not only Python-first teams, but people who are just using Positron for Python.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:50.000
We want them to have a great experience, but also teams that have a lot of R users and Python users. We want them to be able to work effectively within the development environment and switch between the R context and the Python context.

00:21:51.000 --> 00:22:15.000
Just to kind of emphasize what Wes said about polyglot, I mean, today that means R and Python. But the idea is that we've built this foundation that no matter what the next data science language or environment is, we can build the tool for that. So you've got that one place that you can be using all of your favorite data science tools, regardless of what language or what tools that you're using.

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:37.000
Thank you. Realizing we have so many questions that we may not get to, but we will figure out some way to keep that conversation going and answer all these questions. But to deep dive on that a little bit, there was another question that was, I'm using Python and R for analytics and production.

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:46.000
How can Posit Workbench or Connect help us integrate Python scripts and R models into a cohesive and efficient workflow?

00:22:47.000 --> 00:23:08.000
I think the goal of both Workbench and Connect is to put R and Python on equal footing. So regardless of whether you're using R or Python, you can develop your scripts in the same editing environment, and you can publish them to the same environment using the same tools.

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:28.000
So I think that's really about helping both 100% R and 100% Python teams or even individuals work effectively. And then how do we make sure those teams, the R users and the Python users can collaborate as effectively as possible?

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:44.000
And to me, that's mostly happening on the open source side. That's making sure, like on the R side, that we have this nano parquet file so that you can read in R or read and write parquet files, which are a great way of sharing data with your Python using colleagues.

00:23:44.000 --> 00:24:01.000
There's things like the pins package, which we have for both R and Python, that allows you to save data sets and share them with your colleagues really easily. Tools like Veta for model monitoring, they're working with R and Python. Great tables that work with both R and Python.

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:18.000
So having these tools where you end up with like a shared vocabulary and a shared tool set and shared conventions around storing and using data that hopefully ease some of those boundaries a little.

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:26.000
Thank you. I was trying to add those links as quickly as I could, but I might need some help from everybody.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:49.000
Yeah, I see Jeffrey mentioned Orbital, which is another really cool tool, which basically lets you take your tidy models workflows and convert them to SQL. And obviously, once you've got your model predictions computed in SQL, you can deploy that in any database, which is just such a really cool idea.

00:24:50.000 --> 00:25:13.000
Okay, let's take a quick detour to the AI conversation. I see some questions submitted ahead of time on AI and also LLMs. What is Posit's roadmap for LLMs, both for folks developing LLM apps and for developers using Posit products?

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:42.000
I don't know if we're at the point where we have a roadmap, I'd say, but we have a lot of internal skunkworks projects on the go to try and figure out what LLMs mean for data scientists, both for doing data science, whether that's extracting structured data from unstructured text, or writing the code that you use to do data science.

00:25:43.000 --> 00:26:04.000
So we're exploring a bunch. Personally, I've been working on the Alma package for R, which makes it easy to use any of a range of LLM providers from R programmatically. That's hopefully going to go to CRAN tomorrow, or maybe the day after, or maybe Friday, failing that.

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:32.000
And then I think we're really thinking about how should LLMs and PositRAN interact? Is there something special for data scientists? Is this just like kind of a generic programmer software engineering problem and you can integrate with all the existing tools like Continuum or Codium or any of the 17 other LLM VS code extensions that I forget the name of.

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:38.000
But no roadmap, but I think a lot of interest, a lot of excitement and a lot of experiments.

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:56.000
Yeah, I mean, I think one of the things that we're, you know, I think one of the things that we're, you know, we're looking closely at is how, because I assume that a lot of people in the call have used Copilot or have used one of the other LLM VS code extensions like Continuum.

00:26:56.000 --> 00:27:11.000
Like, I personally recently just switched from using Copilot to Continuum. And so you install the Continuum extension. It's basically like a common, it's kind of like an open source Copilot, you know, auto completion, and it does code editing and chat.

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:26.000
Kind of within, and you plug in your own, you know, API key from your preferred model. Like, I'm using Anthropic, like the Anthropic API. Like, it's very, it's very inexpensive to use, but you could also plug in like an open AI API key.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:42.000
